The first time I heard this song was in November 2023. I kept playing it on repeat that day, about 1000 times. At one point, it triggered something inside me. I ran out of the place where I was sitting with some of my close friends.  Everyone was looking for me. They checked the CCTV and searched for me in the direction I had run. They called the cops because they couldn't find me. The guy who found me saw me running and crying on the highway. He stopped to ask if I was okay and gave me water. He asked my name and if I had anyone with me. When he found out I was alone, he told me he was from out of town for a meeting. He suggested we take a room nearby to clean up, and then he would take me to his home. Suddenly, I realized that this guy could kidnap and harm me, and I started crying. I told him I had a best friend nearby and would go to him instead. He offered to take me there, but I didn't want to get in his car. So, I made him walk all the way to my best friend's house. My best friend called everyone to let them know I was safe with him. I've never listened to that song since the incident. Music can be very powerful. Today, I decided to hear it again! The allure of clubs, drugs, new faces, gambling, and avenues‚Äîthese became my chosen escapes from the harsh realities of life. They painted a facade of relief, promising a break from the relentless pressure, even if just for a fleeting moment. "Escapism" becomes an intimate narrative of this journey, depicting the initial allure of these escapes. The song resonates deeply because it encapsulates the cycle of seeking solace in these self-destructive paths, including the allure of these avenues as a means to numb the overwhelming emotions. Initially, these avenues offered a temporary escape, a brief hiatus from the turmoil within. However, their allure soon faded into a haunting descent into a darker realm. The song serves as a haunting reminder of the dangers in seeking refuge through these self-destructive means, illustrating how they ultimately lead to a darker and more isolated place, intensifying the pain instead of offering genuine relief.

I love how this song delves into such ubiquitous and important yet overlooked aspects of human psychology and behavior! In this song, the narrator is faced with a stressor, but clearly makes poor choices and does not effectively cope with their situation despite desperately wanting to escape, as the title of the song suggests, from the stressor and the immense negative emotions it induces. And the narrator is not alone; countless people get caught up in the vicious cycle of repeatedly making poor choices for the sake of taking the easy way out and getting into a state of euphoria, albeit temporarily. Thus, I actually think this song can serve as a great launching point for discussions about wellness and stress management techniques. Specifically, it has raised questions for me on how the narrator could have more effectively dealt with their situation in a manner that's conducive to their well-being. And I'm sure the answers to these questions, though varying from person to person, would have a surprising level of applicability for people across the globe looking to escape, whether physically or mentally, from all sorts of stressors but not knowing how to effectively do so. It's a common trope among humanity that needs to be looked into and addressed!
